Objectif(s) :¶

  • Comprendre les données du serveur météonet individuellement
  • Comprendre le lien entre les différentes données, ainsi que les corrélations entre les différents modèles de MeteoFrance (Arome et Arpege)

Commentaires¶

Les distributions sont globalement similaires. Les moyennes correspondent et les écart-types sont très proches également. La grosse différence réside dans les valeurs extrêmes / outliers qui sont beaucoup plus élevées et nombreuses dans le trainset que dans le testset

In [5]:
nb_lignes = 5
nb_colonnes = 5

données_stations = ["lat","lon","height_sta","number_sta"]
for data in données_stations:
    if data in trainset.columns:
        trainset = trainset.drop(data,axis=1)
    if data in testset.columns:
        testset = testset.drop(data,axis=1)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(nb_lignes,nb_colonnes,figsize=(20,20))
for i in range(nb_lignes):
    for j in range(nb_colonnes):
        sns.distplot(trainset[trainset.columns[nb_lignes*i+j]], color='g', bins=100, hist_kws={'alpha': 0.4}, ax=ax[i][j]);
        sns.distplot(testset[testset.columns[nb_lignes*i+j]], color='r', bins=100, hist_kws={'alpha': 0.4}, ax=ax[i][j]);
fig.legend(["Trainset","Testset"],loc='center left',fontsize='x-large')
plt.show()

Base Checklist¶

Shape Analysis :¶

  • target feature : Ground_truth
  • observations & features : 543, 30
  • features types : qualitatives : 1 , quantitatives : 29
    • Only qualitative feature : Id
    • 4 features have constant value (no variance): number_sta, height_sta, lat, lon ==> Obviously because we are only looking at a single station
      • We need to get rid of these features : no variance ==> no correlation
    • Distributions are pretty different one from each other
    • The feature "month" is qualitative but is the encoding of a qualitative information (12 different integer values)

Features Analysis :¶

  • Target Analysis :
    • Balanced (Y/N) : NO -> Skewed arround 0

Mid-Conclusion¶

We can drop the columns that have no variance (i.e): number_sta, height_sta, lat, lon

We can keep the "Id" column for later so we can have the time dimension ("Id" feature are sorted chronologicaly)

Correlations on features¶

Now we'll try to find which features are strongly correlated with Ground_truth. We'll store them in a var called golden_features_list. We'll reuse our df_num dataset to do so.

In [6]:
trainset_corr = trainset.corr()['Ground_truth'][:-1] # -1 because the latest row is SalePrice
golden_features_list = trainset_corr[abs(trainset_corr) > 0.17].sort_values(ascending=False)
del golden_features_list['Ground_truth']
print("There are {} strongly correlated values with Ground_truth in trainset:\n{}".format(len(golden_features_list), golden_features_list))
print("--------")
testset_corr = testset.corr()['Ground_truth'][:-1] # -1 because the latest row is SalePrice
golden_features_list = testset_corr[abs(testset_corr) > 0.17].sort_values(ascending=False)
del golden_features_list['Ground_truth']
print("There are {} strongly correlated values with Ground_truth in testset:\n{}".format(len(golden_features_list), golden_features_list))

Perfect, we now have a list of strongly correlated values but this list is incomplete as we know that correlation is affected by outliers. So we could proceed as follow:

  • Plot the numerical features and see which ones have very few or explainable outliers
  • Remove the outliers from these features and see which one can have a good correlation without their outliers

Btw, correlation by itself does not always explain the relationship between data so ploting them could even lead us to new insights and in the same manner, check that our correlated values have a linear relationship to the Ground_truth.

For example, relationships such as curvilinear relationship cannot be guessed just by looking at the correlation value so lets take the features we excluded from our correlation table and plot them to see if they show some kind of pattern.

fig1 = plt.figure(figsize=(30,14))
fig1.suptitle('Explaining the trainset using PCA', fontsize=36)
# fig2 = plt.figure()  # more figures are easily accessible
# fig3 = plt.figure()  # more figures are easily accessible

ax221 = fig1.add_subplot(221)  # add subplot into first position in a 2x2 grid (upper left)
ax223 = fig1.add_subplot(223, sharex=ax221)  # add to third position in 2x2 grid (lower left) and sharex with ax11
ax122 = fig1.add_subplot(122)  # add subplot to cover both upper and lower right, in a 2x2 grid. This is the same as the rightmost panel in a 1x2 grid.
## Décroissance de la variance expliquée
ax221.plot(np.arange(1,PCA_df.shape[1],1),pca.explained_variance_ratio_)
ax221.plot(np.arange(1,PCA_df.shape[1],1),pca.explained_variance_ratio_.cumsum())
ax221.legend(["Explained Variance","Cumulated Variance"])
ax221.set_ylabel('Variance explained')
## distribution des composantes principales
ax223.boxplot(PCA_df.drop("Ground_truth",axis=1))
ax223.set_xlabel('How many component to we take ?')
ax223.set_ylabel('Distribution of the component')
## coordonnées et représentation des variables
coord1=pca.components_[0]*np.sqrt(pca.explained_variance_[0])
coord2=pca.components_[1]*np.sqrt(pca.explained_variance_[1])
for i, j, nom in zip(coord1,coord2, X_train.columns):
    ax122.text(i, j, nom)
    ax122.arrow(0,0,i,j,color='black')
ax122.axis((-1.2,1.2,-1.2,1.2))
# cercle
c=plt.Circle((0,0), radius=1, color='gray', fill=False)
ax122.add_patch(c)
ax122.set_xlabel("PCA_0")
ax122.set_ylabel("PCA_1")
plt.show()

from sklearn.svm import LinearSVR
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectFromModel
model = SelectFromModel(LinearSVR(C=0.01)).fit(X_train, y_train)
print("Coefficients :",model.estimator_.coef_)
print("Threshold :",model.threshold_)
print("Support :",model.get_support())
print("Features selected :",model.feature_names_in_[model.get_support()])
X_new = pd.DataFrame(model.transform(X_train),columns=model.feature_names_in_[model.get_support()])
print(X_new.shape)
display(X_new.head())
